            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 12:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(18) The daughter.—So rightly, LXX., Vulg., and many Hebrew MSS. for the ordinary reading son.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(18) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The daughter.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—So rightly, LXX., Vulg., and many Hebrew MSS. for the ordinary reading ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "son.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of Jerimoth the son of David—Jerimoth does not occur in the list of David’s sons (1Chronicles 3:1-8), unless we suppose the name to be a corruption of “Ithream.” Probably he was one of “the sons of the concubines” (1Chronicles 3:9).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Of Jerimoth the son of David",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Jerimoth does not occur in the list of David’s sons (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 3:1-8",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), unless we suppose the name to be a corruption of “Ithream.” Probably he was one of “the sons of the concubines” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 3:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And Abihail.—The and is not in the present Hebrew text, but is supplied by the LXX. “And of Abihail” is probably the meaning, so that both of Mahalath’s parents are named. The LXX. and Vulg. make Abihail a second wife of Rehoboam; but 2Chronicles 11:19-20, as well as the construction of the sentence, make it evident that only one wife is mentioned here. A daughter of David’s eldest brother could hardly become the wife of David’s grandson.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And Abihail.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "and",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " is not in the present Hebrew text, but is supplied by the LXX. “",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "And of",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " Abihail” is probably the meaning, so that both of Mahalath’s parents are named. The LXX. and Vulg. make Abihail a second wife of Rehoboam; but ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 11:19-20",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", as well as the construction of the sentence, make it evident that only one wife is mentioned here. A daughter of David’s eldest brother could hardly become the wife of David’s grandson.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Eliab the son of Jesse.—1Samuel 17:13; 1Chronicles 2:13.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Eliab the son of Jesse.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Samuel 17:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 2:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
