  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 18.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The 'Speaker's Commentary' opportunely  suggests the probability that we may be indebted here to Iddo's \"genealogies\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "daughter",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " here is a correction of the Keri, the Chethiv having been \"son,\" This ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Jerimoth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is the seventh out of a list of eight men of the same name mentioned in the two books of Chronicles. He is not given as one of the children of David's proper wives in either ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 3:1-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or 1 Chronicles 14:4-7; Jerome says it was the Jewish tradition that he was the son of a concubine of David. It is just possible that Jerimoth and Ithream were two names of the same person. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Abihail",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was second cousin of Mahalath. It is not quite clear whether Abihail were wife of Jerimoth and mother of Mahalath, or a second wife now mentioned of Rehoboam. The contents of the next verse not differencing the children there mentioned, and assigning her own to each wife of Rehoboam, if these were two wives of his, favours the former supposition (our Hebrew text being \"and she ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "bare",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",\" not \"which bare\"). When it is said that Abthail was the daughter of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Eliab",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the meaning probably is, as again in ver. 20, granddaughter. (For Eliab, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 16:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 17:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) 2 Chronicles 11:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 11:18-23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", information as to Rehoboam's family relationships. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 11:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Instead of בּן we must read, with the Keri, many MSS, lxx, and Vulg., בּת: Mahalath the daughter of Jerimoth, the son of David. Among the sons of David (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 3:1-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") no Jerimoth is found. If this name be not another form of יתרעם,   ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 3:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Jerimoth must have been a son of one of David's concubines. Before the name אביחיל, ו must have been dropped out, and is to be supplied; so that Mahalath's father and mother are both named: the daughter of Jerimoth the son of David, and Abihail the daughter of Eliab the son of Jesse, i.e., David's eldest brother (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 17:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). For Abihail cannot be held to be a second wife of Rehoboam, because ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
